    <section class="heloc-edu-section">
      <h2 class="heloc-edu-title">Understanding Home Equity Lines of Credit</h2>
      <div class="heloc-cards">
        <div class="heloc-card">
          <h3>How a HELOC Works</h3>
          <p>A HELOC functions similarly to a credit card, but it uses your home as collateral. You are approved for a maximum credit limit based on your home's equity. During the 'draw period' (usually 5-10 years), you can borrow against this limit as needed and typically only pay interest on what you use.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="heloc-card">
          <h3>Draw vs. Repayment Periods</h3>
          <p>Once the draw period ends, you enter the repayment period (typically 10-20 years). You can no longer borrow money, and your monthly payments will increase significantly because you must now pay back the principal balance along with the interest.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="heloc-card">
          <h3>Variable Interest Rates</h3>
          <p>Unlike most primary mortgages or home equity loans, HELOCs usually have variable interest rates tied to the prime rate. This means your monthly payment can fluctuate over time as broader economic interest rates rise or fall.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="heloc-card">
          <h3>The 80% LTV Rule</h3>
          <p>Lenders view HELOCs as riskier than first mortgages. To protect themselves, most limit your total combined debt (mortgage + HELOC) to 80% (sometimes 85% or 90%) of your home's appraised value. This is known as the Loan-to-Value (LTV) ratio.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

