    <section class="heloc-edu-section">
      <h2 class="heloc-edu-title">HELOC vs. Home Equity Loan</h2>
      <div class="heloc-table-wrapper">
        <table class="heloc-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Feature</th>
              <th>HELOC (Line of Credit)</th>
              <th>Home Equity Loan</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Disbursement</strong></td>
              <td>Revolving credit line (borrow as needed)</td>
              <td>Lump sum upfront</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Interest Rate</strong></td>
              <td>Usually variable (can change over time)</td>
              <td>Usually fixed (stays the same)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Payments</strong></td>
              <td>Interest-only during draw period, then principal + interest</td>
              <td>Fixed monthly payments (principal + interest) from day one</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Best For</strong></td>
              <td>Ongoing expenses (renovations, education)</td>
              <td>Single, large expenses (debt consolidation)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <section class="heloc-faq">
      <h2 class="heloc-edu-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="heloc-faq-item">
        <h3 class="heloc-faq-q">How much of a HELOC can I get?</h3>
        <p class="heloc-faq-a">Most lenders allow you to borrow up to 80% or 85% of your home's appraised value, minus what you currently owe on your primary mortgage. This calculator uses a standard 80% Loan-to-Value (LTV) ratio to estimate your available credit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="heloc-faq-item">
        <h3 class="heloc-faq-q">What is the difference between the draw period and repayment period?</h3>
        <p class="heloc-faq-a">The draw period (typically 5-10 years) is when you can borrow money from your HELOC, and you usually only have to make interest payments. The repayment period (typically 10-20 years) follows, during which you can no longer borrow, and your payments include both principal and interest to pay off the balance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="heloc-faq-item">
        <h3 class="heloc-faq-q">Is a HELOC better than a home equity loan?</h3>
        <p class="heloc-faq-a">A HELOC offers flexibility, allowing you to borrow only what you need when you need it, often with a variable rate. A home equity loan provides a lump sum upfront with a fixed interest rate and fixed monthly payments. The better choice depends on whether you have a specific, immediate expense or ongoing financing needs.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="heloc-faq-item">
        <h3 class="heloc-faq-q">How is a HELOC monthly payment calculated?</h3>
        <p class="heloc-faq-a">During the draw period, your minimum payment is typically just the interest on the amount you've borrowed. During the repayment period, your payment is calculated to fully amortize (pay off) the outstanding balance over the remaining term, including both principal and interest.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="heloc-faq-item">
        <h3 class="heloc-faq-q">What does LTV mean in a HELOC?</h3>
        <p class="heloc-faq-a">LTV stands for Loan-to-Value ratio. It compares the total amount of debt secured by your home (including your primary mortgage and the potential HELOC) to the home's appraised value. Lenders use it to determine your risk and maximum credit limit.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

